         <abstract>
            <p>According to his Gadl, the monk <persName ref="PRS1906Ananyao"/> came from the 
               <placeName ref="LOC4564Maragw">Marāgʷǝz district</placeName> of the province <placeName ref="LOC5575Saraye"/>. 
               He was a member of the monastic movement known as Ewostateans, following the guidance and doctrines of 
               <persName ref="PRS3934Ewostate"/>, whose birthplace in <placeName ref="LOC2358DabraS"/> is noted in the Gadl as well as
               his successors <persName ref="PRS2385Bakimos"/> and <persName ref="PRS7769Pawlos"/>. ʾAnānyā travelled extensively. 
               He interceded with <persName ref="PRS7769Pawlos"/> in  <placeName ref="LOC2358DabraS"/> to organise the defence of 
               Ethiopia against Muslim invaders. He succeeded <persName ref="PRS7769Pawlos"/>. One day, he went to 
               <placeName ref="LOC1937Bizan"/>, where he miraculously arrived in one hour instead of taking ten days as usual. Another time, 
               he went to the king and crossed the <placeName ref="LOC5864Takkaz"/> by parting the waters. According to the description, he
               died at the hands of an <persName ref="ETH1973Oromo">Oromo person</persName> in the land of 
               <placeName ref="LOC6408Zaeta"/>. After his death, half of his disciples remained to watch over his body while the other half 
               went to <placeName ref="LOC5191Qata"/> to announce the event. The inhabitants of <placeName ref="LOC5191Qata"/> 
               quarrelled with those of <placeName ref="LOC4545Maqala"/> over the casket of ʾAnānyā. The cries of this quarrel could be heard
               in <placeName ref="LOC2947Endart"/> and in <placeName ref="LOC5685Sera"/>. He was buried in 
               <placeName ref="LOC5191Qata"/> on 11th Maskaram, but <persName ref="PRS5643Iyosayas"/> and his other disciples decided 
               to remove his remains and transfer them to Dabra Ṣarābi, the monastery where he was to rest.</p>
         </abstract>
